content.message: Hello! Do you like rock music?
Hi! I love rock music and it has been for a while now. I think since the 60s.
Yeah, it's definitely a classic and great genre. White snake has had over 50 members through it's history. That's crazy!
I know. The list has its own wikipedia page.
I wonder why so many people ended up leaving/joining the band. Do you know if they were just a specific position switching out, like a guitarist?
I guess they may not have get used to that life style. Did you know that a song became popular because a DJ didn't reveal the band name. Don't remember where it was, but still incredible.
That's pretty interesting. Sonic the hedgehog was supposed to have been in a rock band. I wonder how that would have worked out.
Hahaha. Honestly, I have no idea. I also heard that he have a blond haired human girlfriend named Madonna.
That's really strange. I'm glad he just stayed a video game character. Viktor tsoi kept his job in a boiler room after becoming the biggest rock star in russian history.
russian already sounds like rock anyways. Rock is kind of interesting, even Oklahoma has a state rock song.
That's pretty cool. Did you know the man who assassinated Abraham Lincoln was named after the man who assassinated Julius Caesar?
too much concidence. Abraham Lincoln has a unusual voice. Do you know how he sounded?
Apparently he had a high pitch voice, I never would have guessed that! I always imagined him as having a deep voice for some reason.
Me too. The say that he used to keep his important documents in his hat. That's kind of funny. Now we know why the hat was so high. hahaha
He had so many secrets in there, lol! Lincoln created the secret service the morning he was shot. That seems suspicious.
I think so too.  Abraham Lincoln was the first republican as well.
That's interesting! He started a long line of bearded republicans!
he had done good things as well. He preserved the Union and abolished  slavery.
Yeah, he was very noble and good hearted. He was also a lawyer before becoming a politician!
I wonder if he was a good lawyer.  I heard he also modernized the economy.
Yes,he was a  very good president! Well, it was nice chatting with you!
See you next time
Hi, how are you today? Do you like rock music?
Hi! I do like rock music, I like a little bit of everything.
The state rock song of Oklahoma is "Do You Realize?" by the Flaming Lips. I didn't know that states had rock songs.
Especially a lot of midwestern states seem to have songs attached to them. I was reading that Whitesnake has had over 50 members in its history. They must not be fun to work with.
I guess not. Maybe it's band to put on your resume, then move on. I don't know how much they tour. It could be a tough gig.

Probably some overdosed. I read that a hanson song became the most requested track on a chicago station not because people liked it, but the station created an air of mystery about it by not telling people who sang the song.
That was very smart of them. Get new listeners, more advertising. Probably a boy band is not what most listeners were looking for.
I heard the sonic the hedgehog character was supposed to be a member of a rock band, and had a girlfriend named madonna, but I didn't hear the whole story. Do you know?
Sonic in a rock band? I guess he has the haircut for it. He could probably have joined Whitesnake.
Oh yeah, that would have been good. Are you interested in history? I was reading about Lincoln. He had a high pitched voice, I guess.
That's funny because he was very tall. He kept his important documents inside his hat. I guess that hat was pretty big.

You know, I always mean to do some research to see if he maybe had some kind of genetic disorder. He was so tall, and had such strange bone structure. Especially hearing about his weird voice now, I'm even more curious.
He had a pretty big beard, so I would have expected a deep voice. He was an unusual guy that met a tragic end.
I would expect deep voice too. Did you know he created the secret service the very morning he was assassinated? Ironic.
I guess he recognized that he was at tremendous risk because of the war and his treatment of slaves. I don't know if the secret service could have saved him.
No, I'm sure they couldn't have. John Wilkes Booth father was named after the man that assassinated julius caesar. What a strange story all around.
Yeah, lots of weird connections. Lincoln had a secretary named Kennedy. JFK had a secretary named Lincoln. It's kismet.
I've never heard that. Those types of coincidences are always interesting to me.

We can always find connections if we look hard enough. For example, Lance Henriksen and Bill Paxton are the only two actors to face off against a terminator, an alien and a predator. Connections abound.
Oh sure, I guess Bender from futurama and the terminator both have the same cpu.
that's great! Bender is savage. He really could be a terminator. Never quite get the salary for Arnold though.
I can't believe he gets paid so much. He only said like 100 words in Terminator.
His physique is the key. Plus that Austrian accent.
Its been nice talking to you!
Great chat! Have a good day!
I You have a great day too
Hi! So do you like music? I love rock music and well many other genre's.
Yes, I'm the same! I love music....I didn 't know the band Whitesnake has had over 50 members over time?Thinking the lead singer stayed the same, not sure?
That is something I read too, I do believe the lead singer is the same. There was so much great rock music back in the day!
Oh, I know, Decades. There was so much and people today have no idea how great alot of it was!!
Very true! I really love the electric guitars in Rock, it's all good. I got to see the best bands in concert that's for sure lol
You sound like me! I have been to so many concerts and have bought so much music over the years. I have  alot to refer back to. Do you have favorite bands?
That's awesome! My favorites to name a couple would be Pink Floyd and Aerosmith...so many more! How about you?

Yes, I have seen Pink Floyd a few times and Aerosmith every time they came to our state. I heard they were going to do Las Vegas for awhile. I go back to Elvis, Beatles, all the 70 and 80  90 bands. I have tickets to the Who this year and Bryan Adams so far! lol

Haha! That's awesome, you sound like me, I kept memento's along the as well, In the 90s I went to see Candlebox and the drummer came up to me and handed me his drum stick, and I have met many, I wish I could have seen Ozzy but never did which is a bummer.

I know, I would have like that too! Very cool. Its hard to get the up front seats! lol, While in Texas I saw Rod Stewart and manage to get two balls that night. I went this last year and had second level seat on the side and one of his guys came up to me and a friend and gave us front row center! we were shocked!! Very happy that night!! lol

Wow, that is amazing! You have been to as many concerts or more than I have lol, I just love seeing them so I will pay for up front if I can, I got real close to the Cult and Queensryche, and at a Van Halen concert I saw some famous people next to me.

Really, that's so interesting! One of favorites is Led Zepp Lucky to see them in 77, and then again When Robert Plant and Jimmy Page did a tour together and had close seats. Very Cool. Would have been nice to see them in 2007 in the UK. I think those tickets sold out in minutes at a very high price!

You got to see Led Zeppelin?? Wow, that is awesome. I love those guys! Yes, not always easy to get tickets they sell fast! Especially these days. But just like music we got to see all the great movies too, did you ever see the terminator?
Yes, I enjoyed it. I can't believe he only made $75,000 in the first one!!
I know! But he did make 15 million in the 2nd one so that's great! He only had to speak 18 lines in the Terminator and less than 100 words lol...I would take 75 grand for that!
lol, I know....Have you been to the Terminator ride at Universal?
No I haven't but I did go to Universal studios back in the late 90s and went to the Terminator 3D show, wow I was blown away!! How was the ride?
Yes, that's the one I mean! Where an actor comes out and rides all around on a motorcycle with the gun!! Alot of fun!! The 3D movie was great!!
Yes! That is it, but it seemed like you were on a crazy ride lol. That franchise is worth 3 billion dollars that's pretty amazing for older movies.
Yes, I agree. A fun thing to know about Abraham Lincoln, he kept important papers in his hat and his had a high pitched voice! Who knew?
Really? That's odd about his voice, he looks so rough lol. He was a great president though. And how does it happen that he gets assasinated just after creating the secret service, wow.
I didn't know that either, surprised me. The same morning!  In the films about him he always has a deep voice!! Great chat!!
I know, very bad for the poor guy. Thanks for the chat! I need to go listen to some good Rock music and watch the Terminator now lol! Bye!!

Hello.  Do you like Rock Music?  Rock music is a broad genre of popular music that originated as "rock and roll" in the US in the early 1950s and developed into a range of different styles in the 1960s and later in the UK as well as the US.

Yes I do like rock music! I especially like that a lot of rock artists seem to be down to earth, like even after becoming the biggest rock star in Russian history, Viktor Tsoi kept his job in the boiler room.
That's too funny.  Did you know that the state rock song of Oklahoma is "do you realize?" by the Flaming Lips?
I didn't know states could have state rock songs! I wonder if Illinois' is that song that became the most requested track on that Chicago alt-rock radio station.
That could be.  You mean that Hanson song? Yes, the DJ didn't reveal who sang the song or what band did and so everyone wanted to hear who did it, probably.
Yes that's the one! I think it's interesting that no one knew the band/its members. On the other hand you have bands like Whitesnake, which has had over 50 members throughout it's history.
Whitesnake was one of my favorite bands.  I didn't know that they had so many members that they had their own Wikipedia page about it though. Funny.
I also saw recently on Wikipedia that Sonic the hedgehog was actually supposed to be a member of a rockband, with a blond human girlfriend named Madonna!

Right, very funny. I heard that one, too.  Rock music is actually very interesting, it typically has a 4/4 time signiture using a verse-chorus form but it has become extremely diverse.  Like pop music, lyrics often stress romantic love but also address a wide variety of other themes that are frequently social or even political.
Yeah rock music is definitely fascinating. I like that it draws from a lot of other genres I enjoy, like jazz, classical, blues and folk music.
Yes, I like that too.  Did you see the Terminator?  Did you know that Arnold Schwarzenegger speaks only 18 lines in "The Terminator" and less than 100 words in total?  I didn't realize that before.
I never knew that! I wonder if he had a bigger role in Terminator 2, because I know his pay got significantly bumped from $75k for the first movie to $15 million with the second.

It could be.  I remember that The Terminator movies encompassed a series of films, comics, novels and additional media concerning battles between Skynet's synthetic intelligent machine network and John Connor's Resistance forces and the rest of the human race.
Yeah I'm sure a lot of people appreciated the unique concept of the films. That's probably why as of 2010, the franchise has made over $8 billion in revenue!
Yes, I agree.  Also, scientists developed a real-life T1000 polymer, the world's first self-fixing plastic call the terminator.
That's crazy! It's certainly a unique material. Although I think the Terminator itself isn't the most unique robot; Bender from Futurama shares the same processor, the 6502 cpu.
Yes, and that's same CPU used in Atari 2600, NES, and C64 computer models.  That is amazing.
On a separate note, are you interested in Abraham Lincoln at all? I find it fascinating the father of his assassinator was named after the killer of Julius Caesar.
Yes, the whole Abraham Lincoln saga is strange, in my opinion.  In fact, ironically, Abe created the Secret Service the morning he was fatally shot by John Wilkes Booth.
That's surprising! I wonder if things would have been different if he had created it sooner. I also wonder if his killer found any important documents in Lincoln's hat, where he kept them.
Yes, the answers to which we will probably never find out.  Nice chatting with you, have a good one.
hi how are you doing over there?
Fine. Are you a movie fan?
yes, i am a movie fan. I think that there are many fine movies done by Tom Cruise.
Loved him in Rainman and Jerry McGuire. What do you think of his Mission Impossible films?
he has done a great job finding co-stars that round out the cast. the stories are strong too.
Can't say. Only saw the 1st film. Heard that Angela Bassett is in the latest film. Like her a lot. Which costars are your favorites?
i like simon pegg. ving rhames is also good. there are a couple of others that i forgot.
What do you think about Cruise still doing his own stunts at age 56
I think that he is taking a risk that could stop production and cost a lot of money. i see no need for it.
I agree. Seems odd that Cruise, who has won a Golden Globe Award, never won an Oscar for best actor. He's starred in so many films!
he doesnt do the right kind of films, or doesnt play the right role. in rain man, he did not have a disease. in born on the fourth of july, he probably had a chance but the other films were good.
The film I felt he really earned an Oscar for was Jerry Maguire. So memorable. Do you agree?
he did a great job, but it was a date movie about sports and the academy likes middle brow stuff. weighty material about war and disease.
Date and sports movie, yes, but I'll never forget it. Did you know the M. I. series started in 1996?
there was a tv show before that. the films started in the 90s, i know.
The 60's TV show was a bit silly, but that was part of its appeal; that, and the tape-recorded mission messages... Ever see a re-run?
yeah, probably a couple. it was 60s TV, a bit campy, but what are you going to do? it was the time of odd soundtracks and weirder clothes.
Yes! M. I. films don't seem to take themselves too seriously, I'
which is good. i mean, come on, its a spy show with silly masks and stuff. have fun! its hollywood! escape for two hours.
Agreed. Do you plan to see the latest installment: M. I - Fallout?
I would like to. it got good reviews. Anyway, great chat!
Enjoy your Tom Cruise movie! Cheers!
Are you a tom Cruise fan?
Indeed i think he's a great actor. How about you?
I think he is pretty good. He hasn't won many awards though. Did you know that?
I did not, seems like he would have. Did you like M.I. Fallout?
I haven't seen it. Is that the latest one?
Yeah i give it a 7 but i will still go and see the next one, lol!
Yeah, I'll eventually see it. He's pretty entertaining to be honest. I liked him in Risky Business. Hilarious.
Oh my God you taking me back now. You k now he made 75Million from one movie?
No, I didn't know that. He also built an underground bunker.
Underground bunker! Does he know something we don't, lol. Do you know he vandalized the worlds tallest building?
He's probably losing it a bit to be honest. It wouldn't surprise me.
Yeah apparently back in 2010 he sketched Katie Holmes name into a spire.
Hmmm, is that true? It wouldn't surprise me one bit.
Apparently he does his own stunts, he hung of a airplane at 5,000 feet.
Yeah, that will do the trick. What about inception, have you seen it?
That is one of my all time favorite movies. You?
I saw it. I got confused throughout it. I didn't realize they tried to cast Will Smith. Did you?
I did not glad they didn't I like leo. It took Nolan 10 years to write inception.
Wow, that is a long time to take to write a script. Well, nice chatting with you!
I know but it grossed 828 Million world wide, the 4th highest in 2010.
Nice, well, take it easy.
Hey! Have you heard of Tom Cruise?  What do you think about him doing his own stunts?
I think that he is a great actor, Ive always thought he had mad skills and think its kind of dangerous him doing his own stunts
I totally agree with you but on the other hand, it is kind of cool and makes the movies more realistic.  Although Mission Impossible-Fallout is pretty far out there as far as realism goes.
I agree, movies are becoming unrealistic like that, they have become too scaled, irrational.
I know,  take the Mission Impossible movie for example.  Tom Cruise does a motorcycle chase in Paris.  That's not bad but what is is that there's hardly anyone on the road.  Totally fake.
Yeah totally fake indeed, What I do like about the movie is the different locations, Paris, London, Kashmir.
That is nice.  It's all good to look at. Even Tom Cruise is, and he's 56 years old!
He doesnt look like he has 56 years! I heard he made 75000000 from Mission Impossible 3
That's way too much money!  He gets away with so much stuff, like scratching katie holmes's name in the world's tallest building.
Wow I wonder why he would do that, you know he spent two years learning swordplay and also japanese for a movie.
That's good and shows some depth.  On the other hand, he did spend $10 million  on a bunker that's underground to protect himself from aliens!
That seems a bit paranoid, speaking of movies did you watch Inception?
I don't think I have. Is it any good?
Its actually pretty good, its directed by Christopher Nolan, the movie had $828 million in sales.
Wow! Isn't that the movie with Leonardo DiCaprio in it?
Yea Leonardo is the leading actor, you know two famous actors rejected the part, I bet they regretted that.
Really?  Which ones did that?  Seems like you always hear of big names rejecting parts and then finding out the movies do fantastic.
Will Smith and Brat Pitt are the ones that declined the role, and yeah I bet they though it was going to be a lousy movie.

They are very different that Leonardo. I wonder how the movie would have been with one of them instead.  Tom Cruise has a wide range of movies from Top Gun to Rain Man though. I guess he could do any role.
I bet it would be different for sure, I liked Top Gun I think it was a great movie.
It was a good movie. I did see that one way back in the day!  You got me thinking about that movie, Inception, though.  Wasn't Elon Musk's wife in it?
Yeah she was in it, I though she was pretty good, you should definitely watch it, great movie.
Good afternoon!  A you a fan of movies?
Yes.  Are you a fan of the Mission Impossible film series? Tom Cruise made $75m from Mission Impossible III alone!
I'm not that much of a fan of TC movies as i used to be - maybe because they're all pretty much the same as with MI series.  I do like his early work
Yes I'm not either.  Must be nice to make that kind of money.
You said it - so much money to make essentially the same movie over and over and over... Cocktail is probably my favorite movie of his, and that was decades ago!
They are repetitive. I didn't care for "the Last Samurai" but I did like "Top Gun."
Didn't see the Last Samurai.  I heard they were making a TG sequel - wonder how that will be received?
Probably not as well as it was during the Reagan admin. I didn't realize Elon Musk was in Inception.
I thought I heard about Elon Musk in Inception, but I cannot recall what character he played?  I've seen that movie several times to try to understand it!
No kidding! It was sooooo hard to follow.  It took 10 years for Nolan to write something that confusing.
Talk about a passion project!  Probably needed multiple flow charts to keep track of everything....
Yeah!  I was wrong... It was Musk's wife that was in Inception.  I have no idea what she looks like.  Nolan got his son in the movie too.
Aha!  I was just racking my brain about EM in that movie!  And now I need to figure out who his wife is!!!
Sorry :)  I will say Cruise is dedicated.  He spent two years learning Japanese for the Last Samurai.

I think the concept of the Last Samurai is fascinating, because of what it implies - their only purpose in life is to protect their Master and if they fail to do that they must kill themselves.  In the rare occasion they are without a Master due to other circumstances, they go Ronin (another great movie) and basically become a mercenary.
It's kind of true for Cruise in that he spent $10M for a bunker to protect himself from aliens.  I wonder if that's true.  I know he's a little wacky but that seems a bit too much.
That probably has more do with him being a Scientologist than anything - and the most popular member of that religion to boot!
Yeah I heard of that.  He did etch Katie Holmes name on the top of the Burj Khalifa building.  That's wacky so...
All this TC trivia is a little creepy, feeling like I need a shower!  I almost forgot about the Katie Holmes marriage and kid....  He sure has led a full life
Yes, but I too am having to rethink him.  I really did like him in Risky Business back in the day.  He actually does his stunts like hanging from a plane at 5,000 feet in the newest MI.
Risky Business was great, I was a huge Rebbeca De Mornay fan when I was younger...
Yeah, she is/was hot. Thanks for the chat.  You were excellent!
HI, how are you?
Hello, did uou watch Jurassic World: Fallen Kingdom? what are your thoughs on this movie
I did not see it. Did you?
I did, I  liked it but there are some absurb scenes that didnt make sense at all
Was that the second one with Chris Pratt? I saw the first one, not the second one.
Yeah exactly thats the one with Pratt, he is a velociraptor trainer in the movie
I think I only saw that becuase my wife has a crush on him. I think he may have been shirtless on the trailer so my wife was all in on the movie. Did you like it?
I liked it, I thought it was a nice movie although many parts were unreal like when the volcano explodes and he suddenly can move again.
Ill check it out when it comes to Netflix... I found it odd that the dinosaurs were only on the screen for 15 minutes. Must have had a small CGI budget.
Yeah, Im guessing its a expensive production overall, theres a cool fact and theyy used elephant roars for the t-rex
Really? I recently heard that dinosaurs had really small and meek roars. Not at all like what is projected at movies or on TV.
Maybe they projected it this way so that they would sound scarier, also velociraptors were smaller than projected in movies.
Did you see that the park ride cost more than the movie to make?
No I actually didnt see that, os are you a dinarour fan? I used to love them when I was a little kid
I really did not get into them. That and space were never really that intriguing to me. What about you?
I like them, I  think there are many interesting facts about them I heard scientists recovered a sample of tissue and blood vessels from a T-Rex
Really! Wow, I wonder if they are going to try and clone it. Seems like something we would do and then immediately regret...
Yeah, Jurassic Park should work as a warning lol, that would definetely chage things.
I can see them screwing it up and having some sad creature that only semi-resembles a dinosaur. It would be an ethical dilema for sure.
For sure, it would generate a lot of dispute so anyway do you like how Chris Pratt acts?
I do know some like he worked at Bubba Gump. Nice chatting with you!
Did you watch Jurassic World: Fallen Kingdom?
No, but I have heard some about it.  At least the woman is not running in high heels in this movie!
there are 7 scense that dont make sense at all
I remember talk about one.. Chris Pratt is paralyzed by a tranquilizer dart but then crawls away from molten lava using his paralyzed limbs.  Ha!
Yeah and also the computer parts of the old park still function that is also an absurd thing
Someone was amused by Chris Pratt doing a somersault through the open mouth of a T-Rex.
Is that the scene in which Chris Pratt defies physics? because thats also another ridiculous scene
Apparently he became an athlete after being a house builder.  That seemed strange.
It does seem strange and also how in the middle of the film Pratt developed Nave SEAL skills in a magical way
One reviewer also said that the movie managed to make dinosaurs boring which is hard to do.
I didnt really like the movie, the old Jurassic Park movies were so much better many inconsistensies I do like the leading actor
Apparently the dinosaurs only appear for 15 minutes in the film.  Universal built a ride that cost them more than the film did.
Really? how much did it cost?
The ride cost $110 million while the film was $63 million.
Oh seems like they should spend more in the movie and add more dinasour time in it. Did you hear about the joke Chris Pratt made about the franchise
I think people do get bored looking at too much dinosaur time.  The people are more interesting.  What was Pratt's joke?
He joked about getting the part in 2010 for Jurassic Park 4
Wow!  That is like a premonition.  I guess I will make a joke about winning Power Ball.  I guess you know that the raptors are not computer generated, but are people in dinosaur suits?
Really? they fooled me, I thought that was the computer, it sure takes a long time to render one frame of the T-Rex dinasaur
I suppose that is because of the raindrops and water dripping from T-Rex.
The detail is impressive I guess thats why it takes so long to render them
I think so too.  Well, my wife is asking me to go get some whipping cream for some chicken soup so I am going to wrap it up.  Nice chatting with you.
You wouldnt want to upset the wife! hope you have a nice meal, thanks for the chat and the cool facts.
Have you seen Jurassic world?
I tried watching it but it had some many "believability" problems from talking to velociraptors to costuming.
Yeah it was a bit cheesy. I do like chris pratt though.
Yeah, he's cool even though his sudden Navy SEAL special forces transition was a bit much.
the dinosaurs only appears for 15 minutes
Really?  Seemed like much the same with the predictable humans over dinos where that usually turns out bad.
well it only grossed 63 million and it cost 110 million.
Maybe deviating from CGI had a price.  There were actually people inside of suits for the dinos.
No CGI wow what a rip off. apparently Pratt joked about the lead role.
No surprise there. :)  He's come a long way from waiting tables at 19.  At a Bubba Gump nonetheless...
That's for sure, you know it took 6 hours to render one frame of soaked rained t-rex.
I'm not sure I have the patience for that. Did you know 40% of Americans think humans an dinos lived at the same time?
Wow too funny! James Gun wanted Pratt for Guardians so bad he was willing to CGI him a six pack.
Hee.  He could just exercise.    Wonder if Pratt made a similar deal when Spielberg casted with in JP 4.
Yeah probably. Did you know that all 50 states have Dino Fossil in them.
Pretty cool.  Maybe that's why Canada came up with a glow in the dark dino coin.
Do you know who they were considering for the role in guardians before pratt?
The guy that plays Dennis on Sunny in Philly?
I never watch the show, do you think he would have done a better job?
No.  I do watch the show and it's funny but I can see him doing better.
The original JP's were much better in my opinion.
It looks that way given the dinos were only there 15 minutes.  I also think people are a little burned out on JP.
Yup. well it was nice chatting with you have a good day.
Hi, how are you?
Hello. So I've been reading about Jurassic World: Fallen Kingdom, and Chris Pratt. I haven't seen Fallen Kingdom yet though.
Me too. Is there anything that stood out for you?
About the movie, a little, but I became really interested in the last paragraph when it talked about how scientists expressed the genes of chickens and they grew teeth.
I was a little surprised the dinosaurs were only on film for 15 minutes. Seems like that is not a lot...
They did a good job of really building suspense so when they WERE on screen, it was a big deal!
That's true. Really good point. I loved the Michael Crichton book so I never saw the original Jurassic Park in fear that it would ruin the book. Still haven't seen it...
I think aside from my husband's obsession, the movies feel a bit dated, the older ones do, so it might be harder to see.
I did see the first one with Chris Pratt but that is all I have seen. I think I saw it because my wife may or may not have a thing for Chris Pratt, post-parks and rec when he got ripped.
That's true, he became really hot lol. He was pretty good in Parks and Rec, but as Star Lord he just rocks it. He does really good in silly movies.
Agreed. Can you imagine him waiting on you at Bubba Gump, and then seeing him on tv a few weeks later?
That would be hilarious. Like hey honey, wasn't that our waiter? Oh heck, he's made it to tv! haha.
He wouldn't be the most incredible actor who made the jump. He is talented at those roles though...
Yeah. I haven't seen him in any of the other movies listed like "her" or "delivery man" but the few I have seen, he's pretty funny and sells the role.
The generic role... "delivery man" that's funny. I really liked parks and rec. Did you?

Yeah, though I never finished it because I got tired of how aggressive Leslie Knope was after a while. And it felt weird that her dream became the focus, and Ben's just got crushed. Kinda opposite of Feminism.
HA! Yeah, as someone who works in parks and rec, it got really corny, really fast but I was so impressed with the writing. It was so good.
The writing was great, yes. Chris Pratt and April made the show for me. Happy dog and angry cat!
HA! I always liked the "Damnit Jerry!" when Jerry would not do anything wrong. That poor guy.
I saw him in another Tv show recently, for a one time part, uhh Brooklyn 99, he was funny for a one time bit. Poor guy indeed.
I must have missed that one. I love 99. That's another well written show. Almost got cancelled so I am glad NBC picked it up.
Yes I've been watching it on Hulu episode by episode as it continues!
Nice chatting with you!
Did You hear that clowns copyright their makeup designs on eggshells ?
I never heard that one.  Also, American makeup companies have resumed animal testing so they can sell products in China.
How is animal testing related to selling products in China ? Sorry, I don't get that one...
not sure but maybe it's required to happen before china will buy?  keanu gave $80 million of his $114 million matrix salary to special effects and makeup staff
I wonder why ? Didn't movie producers pay them as well ? ;)
probably not that much
...but they probably did and special effect staff agreed to it... maybe Keanu could give that money to charity... :) Just thinking at loud ;)
Did you know that until 1800 both hand knitting and machine knitting were used to make socks but after 1800 it was mostly machines knitting
It's hard for me to believe that :) I'm sure a lot of people were doing it the old way...
It seems like you probably are right.  The acoustic era gave rise to the expression "put a sock in it" because people put a sock in the phonograph horn to mute it.
lol ;) that's a one way to use it ! :) I wonder what were they doing when wife or husband were too loud or was talking too much :)
lol.  I just learned that best buy and target will price match amazon.
